{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774458169,"nonce":"UcID+snmMa3+ve+8UcidrX+4MYA=","title":"Part 2 analysis: SISU step perturbation (mid-trial context change)","message":"Umbrella: 0af472c (Part 2)\n\n**Motivation:** Test whether SISU causally influences network behavior by changing it mid-trial. If SISU merely correlates with training conditions but does not drive behavior, a mid-trial SISU change should have no effect. Conversely, if the network uses SISU to set its control policy, changing SISU should visibly alter trajectories and neural activity.\n\n**Approach:** Step-change SISU from an initial value to various final values at a specified timestep. Evaluate both at steady state (effector at goal) and during reaching. At steady state: show that SISU perturbation changes neural activity but not force output (null-space effect). During reaching: show that SISU perturbation modulates trajectory properties (deviations, speeds) in the presence of plant perturbations. Compare with/without curl field using dashed/solid line styles.\n\n**Status:** Module exists at `src/rlrmp/modules/analysis/part2/sisu_pert.py`. Implements effector trajectories (steady), network activity (steady), aligned trajectories (reach), and profiles (reach). Uses `get_step_task_input_fn` for the SISU step function.\n\n**References:** Causal intervention paradigm; related to context-dependent modulation in Mante et al. (2013).","files":null}]}